🧾 Problem Statement
🔹 Overview
Enterprise messaging environments built on IBM MQ have evolved organically over time, resulting in highly complex, tightly coupled, and difficult-to-manage topologies. These environments lack standardization, making them challenging to operate, secure, and modernize.
This project addresses the problem of transforming such legacy MQ topologies into simplified, standardized, and automation-ready target architectures using intelligent analysis and rule-based optimization.
🔹 Core Problem
The current (AS-IS) MQ environments exhibit:
Uncontrolled growth of queue managers (QM sprawl)
Complex and non-deterministic routing paths
Applications connected to multiple QMs
Excessive point-to-point channels with unclear ownership
Redundant and unused MQ objects
Inconsistent design patterns across environments
Limited visibility into producer–consumer relationships
These issues lead to:
Increased operational risk
Difficulty in troubleshooting and debugging
High manual effort for onboarding and changes
Lack of scalability and standardization
Challenges in enforcing security and compliance
🔹 Key Pain Points
1. Queue Manager Sprawl
Applications are often connected to multiple queue managers, violating ownership clarity and making dependency tracking difficult.
2. Complex Routing Paths
Messages flow through multiple intermediate queue managers (often unnecessarily), leading to:
Increased latency
Higher failure points
Difficult traceability
3. Ambiguous Ownership and Relationships
Multiple candidate queue managers for a single application
Inconsistent queue naming and alias usage
Lack of clear producer–consumer mapping
4. Redundant and Inefficient Topologies
Routing-only queue managers acting as pass-through nodes
Duplicate or unused queues
Excessive fan-in / fan-out patterns
5. Lack of Standardization
Each part of the system evolves differently, resulting in:
No consistent architecture
Difficult automation
High onboarding effort
6. Data Quality Issues
The input data reflects real-world inconsistencies:
Missing producer/consumer identities
Broken routing paths
Orphan flows
Ambiguous mappings
🔹 Opportunity
This problem presents an opportunity to:
Introduce standardized MQ architecture patterns
Enforce one queue manager per application
Enable deterministic and simplified routing
Reduce topology complexity significantly
Build an automation-first provisioning model
Detect and handle data quality and ambiguity systematically
Support human-in-the-loop decision making for edge cases
🔹 Objective of the Solution
The goal is to:
Analyze the AS-IS MQ topology from a CSV dataset and generate a simplified, constraint-compliant, and production-ready TARGET topology, along with clear reasoning and measurable complexity reduction.
🔹 Constraints to Enforce
The target architecture must strictly follow:
Exactly one Queue Manager per application
Applications connect only to their own QM
Producers write to local queues
Remote queues are used for cross-QM communication
Transmission queues (XMIT) and channels handle inter-QM routing
Consumers read from local queues only
Routing must be deterministic and explainable
🔹 What This Solution Does
This solution:
Parses and analyzes raw MQ topology data
Identifies producer–consumer flows
Detects anomalies and ambiguities
Builds AS-IS complexity metrics
Applies intelligent optimization decisions
Supports optional expert overrides
Generates a TARGET topology in the same schema
Produces validation, comparison, and explanation reports
🔹 Expected Outcome
A clean, simplified MQ topology
Reduced number of routing hops and dependencies
Elimination of redundant MQ components
Clear ownership of queue managers
Improved scalability and maintainability
A fully automation-ready architecture
💡 One-line Summary (optional, nice touch)
“This solution transforms complex, organically grown MQ environments into simplified, standardized, and automation-ready architectures using intelligent analysis, constraint enforcement, and explainable decision-making.”
